Jungle Explorers

by: Ozan Bayraktaroglu

This game was made for my level 2 project at The League of Amazing Programmers.
Click here to download and play!

1. Why I Made This Game

I decided to make this game apposed to any other game because I like to play other platforming games such as Mario and decided to take inspiration from that. Also, I felt that this type of game gave me more variety of what I could implement. Another then that I considered making games such as packman however, they were either too simple or too complex.

2. What I Learned

From the user testing, I learned that while playing a game most people like to have more clear instructions rather than a game where you learn as you play through and figure it out. Some feedback I got from my classmates was to add a score counter into my game, rather than blindly playing through and getting a score. This led me to change the way how my score was calculated and how it was displayed.

3. Architecture of My Game

So in my game, there are many classes. Most of them are for their own objects, or to manage those objects. The Player class is used to keep track of the location of the player, its location, and its values like health. The object manager class tells the player how to interact when hitting the walls, roof, or other things like projectiles. Some of the other classes are just there to make creating levels simpler. The Box class has methods that take in inputs, and based on those creates 3 parts of 1 overall block and puts it into an array list. This saves me the time from manually writing all of those in. The GamePanel method is the one that does all of the drawing, receiving user inputs, and sending signals to other classes after a certain time. On the very top there is the JungleExplorer class. This is just a runner and servers no other purpose

4. Technical Implementation

The reason I decided to use multiple methods and classes, is because of many reasons. One of them is having everything organized. Having everything split up and put in their own places allows me to find the piece of code I am looking for, or change something without having to search for it for 20 minutes. Another reason I used more than 1 class is that some things cannot be used inside of a class with a main method. As far as I can understand this has something to do with the main method being static, however, those objects such as a JPanel can be changed and are not static throughout all instances. Another important part is how the data is held. I decided to use array lists because they give me flexibility on size, and are simple to interact with. I also considered using arrays, however, those have a set length and wouldn't work for constantly changing things like the number of arrows on the screen.

5. Most Challenging Part

The most challenging part of this project would certainly be the physics of how the player interacts with the map. This is because every single side of a "block" had different properties. The bottom of it, when interacted with, disables the player's velocity upwards and the top allows the player to jump again while stopping them from falling. The walls just stop you from moving in 1 direction. The problems occurred when more than 1 of those conditions were met at once. My first attempt to solve this was by using if statements. For example, if the walls are being hit, then don't check if you are standing, or hitting your head. This solved most of my problems, however, it also caused new bugs to arise, such as being able to jump up walls, or use your head to clip into the roof and fly around. In the end, I decided to make special conditions when more than 1 part of a block was hit. Hitting the bottom right corner would push you left, but wouldn't stop your y velocity, all the while preventing the player from clipping into it.

6. Future Fixes and Updates

Some improvements or fixes I may want to make in the future might be to change the way that the player interacts with the environment and how the music system. I would want to fix the player interaction because 1/10 times there is a small bug that allows you to walk a couple of pixels into the wall. To solve this you just have to walk the other direction, however, it is still annoying. The music system is also very obnoxious and there is no option to adjust the volume. The final big thing I would want to work on is the graphics. Many parts of my game are just solidly colored pieces. There are a couple of drawn parts and images. The player I would certainly try to redraw and make a background that fits more with the title screen.
